  "judgment": "The concept budget is spent upside-down. Users live in roughly 645 public types (Core + Data inner ring + Web nucleus + Cache + Jobs + Vector + Security.Trust + their 1-2 chosen connectors) — about 27% of the 2,351-type surface. The other 73% splits three ways: (1) the periphery group alone carries 531 types/49k LOC (23% of all types, 26% of all code) with consumption measured in single samples — KoanContext (154 types, #2 in the framework), Canon (74), Backup pair (96 across Data+Web), ZenGarden (47), Secrets (25, zero external consumers), Web.Auth.Roles (32, zero refs); (2) the AI vertical spends 311 types + 6 of the framework's 17 root facades + a 96-type contracts DTO package on exactly one sample (S18.Prism); (3) connector long-tail is structurally fine (Reference=Intent) but inflates raw counts. Three structural findings beyond raw disproportion: the condemned Orchestration stack's vocabulary is load-bearing (Orchestration.Abstractions: 37 types, 10 of the 76 attributes, referenced by 24 projects — condemning the CLI did not condemn its annotation surface); periphery leaks INTO the settled ring (Mongo/Weaviate/Ollama/S3 connectors hard-depend on Koan.ZenGarden.Core; Koan.Web hard-depends on Koan.Scheduling); and the mandatory entry hall is the single fattest package (Koan.Core: 224 types, 73 static classes, 20 Options — bigger than Cache+Jobs+Messaging pillars combined), so every user pays the maximum-surface toll on day one. Counter-evidence that the redesign discipline works: Cache (78 types/7 projects) and Jobs (49 types/2 projects) deliver flagship pillars at ~1/3 the type cost of equivalent legacy strata, with attribute-first DX (8 attributes total). The annotation vocabulary (76 attributes, 4 with duplicate definitions) and config surface (170 Options + 77 Add* methods vs the promised single AddKoan()) are each ~2.5-3x what the settled core actually needs. Smaller drift markers: Koan.Data.Direct documented in CLAUDE.md but has zero Project